252
00:12:58.361 --> 00:13:00.989
He's rushed away in the
back of an ambulance

253
00:13:00.989 --> 00:13:03.241
to hide him from public view.

254
00:13:18.715 --> 00:13:21.551
- His 21-year fascist
reign is over.

255
00:13:28.683 --> 00:13:30.435
- The fall of Mussolini

256
00:13:30.435 --> 00:13:32.270
leads to a very confusing
situation.

257
00:13:32.270 --> 00:13:35.481
The new head of state is the
marshal of the Italian army.

258
00:13:35.481 --> 00:13:37.191
Pietro Badoglio.

259
00:13:37.191 --> 00:13:38.568
He actually makes
an announcement

260
00:13:38.568 --> 00:13:39.652
that the war goes on.

261
00:13:39.652 --> 00:13:42.321
"We remain Germany's
loyal ally."

262
00:13:43.990 --> 00:13:46.200
- After
Mussolini is deposed.

263
00:13:46.200 --> 00:13:48.202
FDR addresses the nation.

264
00:13:48.202 --> 00:13:50.246
- My fellow Americans.

265
00:13:50.246 --> 00:13:53.041
our terms to Italy
are still the same.

266
00:13:53.041 --> 00:13:55.043
unconditional surrender.

267
00:13:56.210 --> 00:13:59.005
- Publicly. Badoglio
states repeatedly

268
00:13:59.005 --> 00:14:02.133
that the war effort is going
on alongside the Germans.

269
00:14:02.133 --> 00:14:06.763
Privately. he is actually
starting to make arrangements

270
00:14:06.763 --> 00:14:09.265
for the Italians to
get out of the war.

271
00:14:11.601 --> 00:14:13.561
- Badoglio signals
that Italy might be open

272
00:14:13.561 --> 00:14:15.229
to an armistice.

273
00:14:17.315 --> 00:14:18.733
He sends one of his generals

274
00:14:18.733 --> 00:14:22.361
to secretly negotiate
directly with the Allies.

275
00:14:23.404 --> 00:14:26.074
- Badoglio might
wish to surrender.

276
00:14:26.074 --> 00:14:28.242
but he needs to have
someone at his back.

277
00:14:28.242 --> 00:14:30.703
He knows that there
will be retribution

278
00:14:30.703 --> 00:14:33.122
from the angriest man
in Europe at the time.

279
00:14:33.122 --> 00:14:35.041
and that will be Adolf Hitler.

280
00:14:41.631 --> 00:14:43.841
- In Sicily. Patton's
army leaves Palermo

281
00:14:43.841 --> 00:14:45.426
to get to Messina.

282
00:14:45.426 --> 00:14:47.637
while the British are
advancing from the south.

283
00:14:47.637 --> 00:14:49.889
Meanwhile. the Germans
are taking advantage

284
00:14:49.889 --> 00:14:52.600
of the delay in
getting to Messina

285
00:14:52.600 --> 00:14:54.560
to begin getting off the island.

286
00:14:57.730 --> 00:15:00.024
It's effectively
the German Dunkirk.

287
00:15:00.024 --> 00:15:02.652
because pretty much
everyone who could walk

288
00:15:02.652 --> 00:15:05.113
and was able-bodied. got off.

289
00:15:05.113 --> 00:15:07.865
and not only that. they got
off with all their equipment.

290
00:15:09.325 --> 00:15:11.869
- The entire purpose of
the Allied operational plan

291
00:15:11.869 --> 00:15:15.873
was to trap the Germans
on Sicily. and they fail.

292
00:15:17.583 --> 00:15:18.960
- Still. things in
Sicily

293
00:15:18.960 --> 00:15:21.087
go pretty much as
Churchill would've wished.

294
00:15:21.087 --> 00:15:23.631
Not only do Allied
troops successfully

295
00:15:23.631 --> 00:15:25.550
drive Axis forces
outta of Sicily.

296
00:15:25.550 --> 00:15:27.635
and it also proves
to be the death nail

297
00:15:27.635 --> 00:15:29.470
of Mussolini's fascist regime.

298
00:15:34.684 --> 00:15:35.726
- With
the potential deal

299
00:15:35.935 --> 00:15:38.604
for an Italian
surrender in the works.

300
00:15:38.604 --> 00:15:41.399
FDR and Churchill
meet in Quebec.

301
00:15:42.316 --> 00:15:43.651
- And it's at this point

302
00:15:43.651 --> 00:15:45.403
that Churchill is able
to say to Roosevelt.

303
00:15:45.403 --> 00:15:48.489
"Look. the Italians are
pulling out of the war.

304
00:15:48.489 --> 00:15:51.367
We have an opportunity
bloodlessly take

305
00:15:51.367 --> 00:15:52.910
the Italian peninsula.

306
00:15:52.910 --> 00:15:55.204
You know. what's not to like
in this operation?"

307
00:15:55.204 --> 00:15:57.290
- Churchill says. "The
Italians are begging us

308
00:15:57.290 --> 00:16:00.042
to come and help liberate
them and switch sides.

309
00:16:00.042 --> 00:16:02.003
We could be in Rome in
a couple of weeks here.

310
00:16:02.003 --> 00:16:04.839
If we land in Italy.
it'll be a cakewalk.

311
00:16:04.839 --> 00:16:06.841
We can't do Sicily
and then go home."

312
00:16:07.842 --> 00:16:09.093
- FDR agrees.

313
00:16:09.343 --> 00:16:12.346
but only with assurance
that Operation Overlord

314
00:16:12.346 --> 00:16:15.474
will remain the Allies'
highest priority.

315
00:16:15.474 --> 00:16:17.435
- The difficult trade off
in the Italian campaign

316
00:16:17.435 --> 00:16:18.769
is that the key resources.

317
00:16:18.769 --> 00:16:21.564
the landing craft
and the best troops.

318
00:16:21.564 --> 00:16:24.400
are gonna go back to the
UK to prepare for D-Day.

319
00:16:26.402 --> 00:16:29.280
- Supreme Allied
Commander Dwight Eisenhower

320
00:16:29.280 --> 00:16:31.574
now picks one of America's
youngest generals

321
00:16:31.574 --> 00:16:34.118
to lead the Italian invasion.

322
00:16:34.118 --> 00:16:38.247
Mark Clark. commander
of the US Fifth Army.

323
00:16:38.247 --> 00:16:41.209
- Clark has a flare
for showmanship.

324
00:16:41.209 --> 00:16:43.085
Because once you pin on a star.

325
00:16:43.085 --> 00:16:46.464
you're also becoming a little
bit of a politician as well.

326
00:16:46.464 --> 00:16:48.174
- Mark Clark has an
immense amount of talent.

327
00:16:48.174 --> 00:16:51.010
but he also has a
corresponding ego.

328
00:16:51.010 --> 00:16:52.845
He travels with a press corps.

329
00:16:52.845 --> 00:16:55.431
He will only let them take
pictures of his favorite side.

330
00:16:55.431 --> 00:16:56.724
which I think is his left side.

331
00:16:56.724 --> 00:16:58.768
based on all the
pictures we see of him.

332
00:17:02.688 --> 00:17:04.440
- The Allied
strategy in Italy

333
00:17:04.440 --> 00:17:06.400
calls for two large forces.

334
00:17:07.484 --> 00:17:09.987
The first will land
in and Calabria.

335
00:17:09.987 --> 00:17:13.031
and the second will land a
few days later at Salerno.

336
00:17:14.367 --> 00:17:17.286
The two forces will then link.
and push north towards Rome.

337
00:17:23.084 --> 00:17:25.877
At Calabria.
Montgomery's Eighth Army

338
00:17:25.877 --> 00:17:27.797
lands almost uncontested

339
00:17:28.923 --> 00:17:30.800
- Badoglio was supposed
to take to the airwaves

340
00:17:30.800 --> 00:17:32.051
on the evening of September 8th

341
00:17:32.051 --> 00:17:33.719
and announce the
Italian surrender.

342
00:17:33.719 --> 00:17:35.721
and this is crucial to the plan.

343
00:17:35.721 --> 00:17:38.224
because it will tell the
hundreds of thousands

344
00:17:38.224 --> 00:17:41.352
of Italian troops how in
beach defense positions

345
00:17:41.352 --> 00:17:44.480
not to fire at the
Allies as they land.

346
00:17:46.774 --> 00:17:47.733
- At
his headquarters.

347
00:17:47.733 --> 00:17:50.361
Eisenhower waits by his radio.

348
00:17:50.361 --> 00:17:53.322
The Salerno landings
are just hours away.

349
00:17:58.077 --> 00:18:00.371
- 6:30 comes. no
Badoglio.

350
00:18:00.371 --> 00:18:02.873
Seven o'clock. no Badoglio.

351
00:18:02.873 --> 00:18:07.086
The entire plan hinges
on a well announced.

352
00:18:07.086 --> 00:18:09.463
orderly Italian surrender.

353
00:18:10.756 --> 00:18:12.633
- Eisenhower
decides to force the issue

354
00:18:12.633 --> 00:18:14.010
by going on the radio himself.

355
00:18:15.803 --> 00:18:17.054
- The Italian government

356
00:18:17.346 --> 00:18:19.640
has surrendered its armed
forces unconditionally.

357
00:18:20.725 --> 00:18:23.561
All Italians who now
act to help eject

358
00:18:23.561 --> 00:18:26.188
the German aggressor
from Italian soil

359
00:18:26.188 --> 00:18:27.523
will have the assistance

360
00:18:27.523 --> 00:18:29.442
and the support of
the United Nations.

361
00:18:33.029 --> 00:18:35.197
- Hitler
anticipates the announcement

362
00:18:35.197 --> 00:18:36.240
of the armistice.

363
00:18:37.325 --> 00:18:39.118
- From the moment
Mussolini falls.

364
00:18:39.118 --> 00:18:41.203
Hitler's convinced that
Badoglio's government

365
00:18:41.203 --> 00:18:44.081
is going to withdraw
from the war.

366
00:18:44.081 --> 00:18:45.708
- For weeks.

367
00:18:45.708 --> 00:18:48.961
Hitler has been moving
German troops into Italy.

368
00:18:48.961 --> 00:18:51.922
He orders Operation Axis.

369
00:18:51.922 --> 00:18:53.507
- The Germans have an
operation

370
00:18:53.507 --> 00:18:54.884
they've been
preparing.

371
00:18:55.051 --> 00:18:57.470
which is that. if the
Italians do the dirty on us.

372
00:18:57.470 --> 00:18:58.846
we're gonna disarm them

373
00:18:59.096 --> 00:19:02.600
and we're gonna take over
the security of all of Italy.

374
00:19:02.600 --> 00:19:05.519
- Italy will
become an occupied nation.

375
00:19:17.615 --> 00:19:21.827
- Operation Axis is the
disarmament of the Italian army

376
00:19:21.827 --> 00:19:25.873
and the occupation of
the entire Italian Boot

377
00:19:25.873 --> 00:19:27.083
by German forces.

378
00:19:29.377 --> 00:19:32.004
It occurs with
lightning rapidity.

379
00:19:34.882 --> 00:19:38.386
The Italian army is
on its back foot.

380
00:19:38.386 --> 00:19:41.305
They aren't so sure about
who they should be firing at.

381
00:19:41.305 --> 00:19:42.306
if anyone.

382
00:19:45.685 --> 00:19:48.187
- Local Italian
resistance movements

383
00:19:48.187 --> 00:19:50.398
form and fight the Germans.

384
00:19:52.233 --> 00:19:54.443
Nazi retaliation is fierce.

385
00:19:54.443 --> 00:19:57.071
- The Italians were
being executed by the Germans

386
00:19:57.071 --> 00:19:58.364
after they switched sides.

387
00:19:58.364 --> 00:19:59.323
There were a lot of
terrible things going on.

388
00:19:59.323 --> 00:20:00.282
villages wiped out.

389
00:20:08.374 --> 00:20:10.000
- When the
Allied invasion force

390
00:20:10.000 --> 00:20:11.585
lands at Salerno.

391
00:20:14.004 --> 00:20:17.675
they believe they'll be
welcomed by Italian troops.

392
00:20:20.469 --> 00:20:23.431
- Underlying this
operational plan is intelligence

393
00:20:23.431 --> 00:20:25.891
that the German army
may evacuate Italy.

394
00:20:25.891 --> 00:20:29.311
that it has no desire
to defend Italy.

395
00:20:29.311 --> 00:20:32.606
If all goes well. the
Allies should be up to Rome

396
00:20:32.606 --> 00:20:35.025
with almost no
casualties at all.

397
00:20:36.277 --> 00:20:37.403
- So what they're gonna
do is they're gonna land

398
00:20:37.403 --> 00:20:39.405
without any pre-bombardment.

399
00:20:39.405 --> 00:20:41.782
and they're gonna hope
for tactical surprise.

400
00:20:43.993 --> 00:20:46.036
- The Allies are
expecting to meet

401
00:20:46.036 --> 00:20:47.163
happy Italian
faces.

402
00:20:47.413 --> 00:20:50.207
perhaps handshakes. taking
over Italian positions

403
00:20:50.207 --> 00:20:52.042
now that Italy had surrendered.

404
00:20:52.042 --> 00:20:54.962
and instead. what the troops
at Salerno experienced

405
00:20:54.962 --> 00:20:57.631
was a wall of German fire.

406
00:21:10.811 --> 00:21:12.438
- The whole of the beach

407
00:21:12.438 --> 00:21:14.148
is being saturated with
shellfire.

408
00:21:16.108 --> 00:21:17.443
It's an absolute inferno.

409
00:21:23.657 --> 00:21:27.244
It was a grim experience for
those first few crucial days

410
00:21:27.244 --> 00:21:29.997
in which they're trying
to defend the beachhead.

411
00:21:34.877 --> 00:21:36.837
And it's the fighting at Salerno

412
00:21:36.837 --> 00:21:38.047
that really convinces Hitler

413
00:21:38.214 --> 00:21:40.424
to make them fight for
every inch of Italy.

414
00:21:43.844 --> 00:21:47.264
- Hitler moves
more forces to defend Italy.

415
00:21:52.603 --> 00:21:54.563
He also discovers that Mussolini

416
00:21:54.563 --> 00:21:57.441
is being held at a hotel
in the Apennine Mountains.

417
00:21:58.442 --> 00:22:00.069
and decides to take action.

418
00:22:01.320 --> 00:22:03.948
- Hitler just can't
quit Mussolini. apparently.

419
00:22:03.948 --> 00:22:07.159
He orders a commando
raid onto the Gran Sasso

420
00:22:07.159 --> 00:22:09.870
to rescue Benito Mussolini.

421
00:22:12.122 --> 00:22:14.083
That force lands.

422
00:22:14.083 --> 00:22:16.877
overcomes Mussolini's guards.

423
00:22:19.755 --> 00:22:21.924
- Mussolini
is flown back to Germany.

424
00:22:24.426 --> 00:22:26.470
- Hitler thinks that
Mussolini

425
00:22:26.470 --> 00:22:29.723
would give legitimacy to the
German occupation of Italy.

426
00:22:31.016 --> 00:22:33.561
- For the rest of the
war. Mussolini will be ruling

427
00:22:33.561 --> 00:22:36.647
a kind of puppet regime
in northern Italy.

428
00:22:36.647 --> 00:22:38.482
But he's a shadow of the figure

429
00:22:38.482 --> 00:22:42.236
who used to strut across the
world stage in the 1930s.

430
00:22:42.236 --> 00:22:44.446
The situation has
changed drastically

431
00:22:44.446 --> 00:22:47.867
since Mussolini was the top
dog and Hitler the imitator.

432
00:22:47.867 --> 00:22:50.911
to now. Mussolini
as Hitler's lap dog.

433
00:23:00.087 --> 00:23:02.965
- After a massive
air and naval assault.

434
00:23:02.965 --> 00:23:07.803
Clark's Fifth Army breaks out
of Salerno and moves inland.

435
00:23:09.138 --> 00:23:12.600
- A modern mechanized
army is going to experience

436
00:23:12.600 --> 00:23:15.144
great difficulty
in driving north.

437
00:23:15.144 --> 00:23:16.562
because the Germans recognized.

438
00:23:16.562 --> 00:23:18.564
the terrain's gonna do
half the work for us.

439
00:23:21.025 --> 00:23:25.070
- Mountain ranges.
ravines. and fast flowing rivers

440
00:23:25.070 --> 00:23:28.866
made Italy a sort
of natural fortress.

441
00:23:31.493 --> 00:23:33.120
- What the Germans
do effectively

442
00:23:33.120 --> 00:23:34.747
is scorched earth policy.

443
00:23:34.747 --> 00:23:36.165
They rip up the railway tracks.

444
00:23:36.165 --> 00:23:37.958
they flood the river valleys.

445
00:23:37.958 --> 00:23:41.003
They make it almost impossible
to move through this terrain

446
00:23:41.003 --> 00:23:42.713
unless you've taken
the high ground.

447
00:23:44.673 --> 00:23:48.510
It was very clear very quickly
that they were gonna struggle

448
00:23:48.510 --> 00:23:50.846
to fight their way up
the Italian peninsula.

449
00:23:52.640 --> 00:23:54.475
General Mark Clark relabeled

450
00:23:54.475 --> 00:23:57.227
Churchill's description of
Italy as the soft underbelly

451
00:23:57.227 --> 00:23:59.229
as the tough old gut.

452
00:24:07.404 --> 00:24:10.449
- It is said
that all roads lead to Rome.

453
00:24:10.449 --> 00:24:13.077
but in the fall of 1943.

454
00:24:13.077 --> 00:24:15.120
for the Allies.
there was only one.

455
00:24:18.040 --> 00:24:19.249
Highway 6.

456
00:24:20.834 --> 00:24:24.171
- As Allied forces are
lured deeper and deeper

457
00:24:24.171 --> 00:24:26.590
by moving north up Highway 6.

458
00:24:26.590 --> 00:24:28.425
the German strategy
very quickly becomes.

459
00:24:28.425 --> 00:24:30.636
we're going to set up a
series of defensive lines.

460
00:24:30.636 --> 00:24:33.722
and you come to us. and
we will then maul you.

461
00:24:40.104 --> 00:24:43.440
- It looked a lot like
World War I defenses look.

462
00:24:44.733 --> 00:24:46.527
There are mines. and
mortars. and machine guns.

463
00:24:48.362 --> 00:24:50.572
On the high ground. you
have artillery observers.

464
00:24:50.572 --> 00:24:53.283
who could have a full view
of the advance of the Allies.

465
00:24:53.283 --> 00:24:56.203
and they would call artillery
to fire on the advances.

466
00:24:58.122 --> 00:25:01.291
The frustration grows with the
costliness of this advance.

467
00:25:01.291 --> 00:25:04.044
the slowness of this
advance up the Boot.

468
00:25:05.796 --> 00:25:07.172
- There's some
historical wisdom here.

469
00:25:07.339 --> 00:25:10.009
and it traces back to the
great Napoleon who once said.

470
00:25:10.009 --> 00:25:12.761
"Italy is a boot.
and like all boots.

471
00:25:12.761 --> 00:25:14.680
has to be entered from the top."

472
00:25:14.680 --> 00:25:16.306
where there's a
nice broad plain.

473
00:25:16.306 --> 00:25:17.725
plenty of room to maneuver.

474
00:25:17.725 --> 00:25:20.561
- To fight up from
the toe of Italy

475
00:25:20.561 --> 00:25:22.271
after coming from Sicily...

476
00:25:22.271 --> 00:25:24.106
Look at the terrain of Italy.

477
00:25:24.106 --> 00:25:27.109
Big mountain range all
down the center spine.

478
00:25:27.109 --> 00:25:28.652
This is the big
problem in Italy.

479
00:25:28.652 --> 00:25:31.280
Who would wanna put an
army into that area.

480
00:25:31.280 --> 00:25:32.489
especially if it's raining?

481
00:25:34.366 --> 00:25:36.744
- It rains every day.

482
00:25:36.744 --> 00:25:38.829
And General Clark once said.

483
00:25:38.829 --> 00:25:41.081
"Anyone who ever talks
about sunny Italy

484
00:25:41.081 --> 00:25:42.666
should be here in October."

485
00:25:42.666 --> 00:25:44.626
which is when the
Allies were there.

486
00:25:46.003 --> 00:25:49.465
Gains are measured not in
miles. but often in yards.

487
00:25:50.924 --> 00:25:54.428
The Italian campaign soon turns
into a slog for the Allies.

488
00:25:54.428 --> 00:25:55.846
- And it's sapping
their energy.

489
00:25:55.846 --> 00:25:58.474
They're wet. they're
cold. they're tired.

490
00:25:58.474 --> 00:26:02.352
All of that is draining
morale. as well as manpower.

491
00:26:03.604 --> 00:26:05.314
One of the things
that they resort to

492
00:26:05.314 --> 00:26:08.067
is using mules to
carry supplies forward.

493
00:26:08.067 --> 00:26:11.278
'cause at least mules can get
through that kind of terrain

494
00:26:11.278 --> 00:26:12.905
in those kind of conditions.

495
00:26:14.198 --> 00:26:16.325
- I think it's fair to
say. when the war began.

496
00:26:16.325 --> 00:26:18.243
in the war department
in Washington.

497
00:26:18.243 --> 00:26:19.745
no one was thinking of mules.

498
00:26:24.041 --> 00:26:26.668
- It was arguably the
most horrendous fighting

499
00:26:26.668 --> 00:26:28.670
that the Western Allies
had to experience

500
00:26:28.670 --> 00:26:30.547
in the whole of the
European theater.

501
00:26:32.091 --> 00:26:33.967
There's no question that
some of the Americans

502
00:26:33.967 --> 00:26:36.762
who've given the go ahead
for the Italian campaign

503
00:26:36.762 --> 00:26:38.639
are now having second thoughts.

504
00:26:40.516 --> 00:26:42.392
- Churchill and the
British commanders

505
00:26:42.392 --> 00:26:44.228
promised the Americans
that. basically.

506
00:26:44.228 --> 00:26:46.271
Italy would fall
relatively quickly.

507
00:26:48.732 --> 00:26:51.318
- Churchill argues
again and again

508
00:26:51.318 --> 00:26:54.321
that it would be
folly not to continue

509
00:26:54.321 --> 00:26:58.200
once one has set out on
the Italian campaign.

510
00:26:58.200 --> 00:27:01.829
arguing they must
capitalize on their gains.

511
00:27:01.829 --> 00:27:03.288
- What do you do.
evacuate Italy?

512
00:27:03.288 --> 00:27:05.749
No. you fight the
enemy in front of you.

513
00:27:05.749 --> 00:27:08.710
Before you know it. you're
embroiled in a massive. costly.

514
00:27:08.710 --> 00:27:10.254
brutal war in Italy.

515
00:27:13.006 --> 00:27:16.009
- Highway 6
snakes into the Liri Valley

516
00:27:16.009 --> 00:27:18.720
on its way up the
Italian peninsula.

517
00:27:22.891 --> 00:27:27.145
Overlooking the valley is
a 1.700-foot rocky peak

518
00:27:27.145 --> 00:27:28.480
called Monte Cassino.

519
00:27:31.275 --> 00:27:35.153
Perched on top is a sixth
century Benedictine abbey.

520
00:27:36.572 --> 00:27:39.283
Monte Cassino is
the strong point

521
00:27:39.283 --> 00:27:41.869
of the German's
defensive formation.

522
00:27:41.869 --> 00:27:43.203
the Gustav Line.

523
00:27:46.248 --> 00:27:48.750
- It must have seemed to
the Allies.

524
00:27:48.750 --> 00:27:50.085
as they gazed up
there.

525
00:27:50.210 --> 00:27:52.004
that this is a kind of
perfect defensive position

526
00:27:52.004 --> 00:27:54.006
for the Germans to use.

527
00:27:54.006 --> 00:27:56.842
- From the commanding
heights of this terrain.

528
00:27:56.842 --> 00:27:58.802
the Germans can rain down

529
00:27:58.802 --> 00:28:01.972
accurate and effective
artillery fire at all times.

530
00:28:04.349 --> 00:28:07.603
- There is no way
to get to Rome

531
00:28:07.603 --> 00:28:10.480
without in some way
dealing with Monte Cassino.

532
00:28:12.482 --> 00:28:15.986
- The Allies hope
to get to Rome by Christmas.

533
00:28:15.986 --> 00:28:18.447
but it's here in the
shadow of Monte Cassino

534
00:28:18.447 --> 00:28:20.782
that the advance stalls.

535
00:28:26.204 --> 00:28:30.292
In November. Allied
leaders gather in Tehran.

536
00:28:30.292 --> 00:28:34.296
FDR is meeting Stalin
for the first time.

537
00:28:34.296 --> 00:28:36.131
- And the first thing
that happens

538
00:28:36.131 --> 00:28:37.716
is Roosevelt and
Stalin

539
00:28:37.716 --> 00:28:41.345
seem insistent on building
their own relationship.

540
00:28:41.345 --> 00:28:43.889
sometimes freezing
Churchill out.

541
00:28:43.889 --> 00:28:45.682
and he takes this
really badly.

542
00:28:47.351 --> 00:28:53.482
- He has to cede center
stage with Roosevelt to Stalin.

543
00:28:53.815 --> 00:28:56.360
And Churchill is in an
interesting kind of

544
00:28:56.360 --> 00:28:57.361
no man's land.

545
00:28:58.403 --> 00:29:00.197
- There's this old line

546
00:29:00.197 --> 00:29:02.282
that Stalin didn't know much
English. but he knew two words.

547
00:29:02.282 --> 00:29:03.533
second front.

548
00:29:03.700 --> 00:29:06.453
because he said it over
and over and over again.

549
00:29:06.453 --> 00:29:08.830
And when Stalin
says second front.

550
00:29:08.830 --> 00:29:11.792
he doesn't mean Sicily
or even mainland Italy.

551
00:29:11.792 --> 00:29:13.043
he means France.

552
00:29:14.878 --> 00:29:18.840
- Churchill says. "I was
the little British donkey

553
00:29:18.840 --> 00:29:21.843
sitting between the
great American eagle

554
00:29:21.843 --> 00:29:23.512
and the Soviet bear.

555
00:29:23.512 --> 00:29:26.264
and I was the only one
who knew the way home."

556
00:29:27.808 --> 00:29:30.227
- Churchill is still
sticking

557
00:29:30.227 --> 00:29:31.561
with his Mediterranean
plan.

558
00:29:31.561 --> 00:29:34.272
But he knows that.
coming out of Tehran.

559
00:29:34.272 --> 00:29:36.483
it's really important
to be able to go back

560
00:29:36.483 --> 00:29:38.193
and win this victory.

561
00:29:40.529 --> 00:29:42.364
- Winston Churchill.
the master of

562
00:29:42.364 --> 00:29:43.281
out-of-the box
thinking.

563
00:29:43.281 --> 00:29:45.200
has an idea for a left hook.

564
00:29:45.200 --> 00:29:48.161
an amphibious landing on
the western shore of Italy

565
00:29:48.161 --> 00:29:50.205
behind the Gustav Line.

566
00:29:51.957 --> 00:29:54.001
- Troops
will land at Anzio.

567
00:29:54.001 --> 00:29:56.878
50 miles behind the
German forces.

568
00:29:56.878 --> 00:29:58.213
then drive inland.

569
00:29:58.422 --> 00:30:01.633
drawing German defenders
away from Monte Cassino.

570
00:30:02.467 --> 00:30:03.802
- Winston Churchill
thinks

571
00:30:03.802 --> 00:30:05.762
that this could break
the whole thing free.

572
00:30:05.762 --> 00:30:09.307
This is the wildcat we need
to shatter this stalemate.

573
00:30:10.851 --> 00:30:12.477
- The Allies
agree to do it.

574
00:30:12.477 --> 00:30:14.771
mainly because Churchill
is convinced it can work.

575
00:30:16.314 --> 00:30:18.567
- But because so many
men and landing craft

576
00:30:18.567 --> 00:30:22.070
have been shipped back to
Britain to prepare for D-Day.

577
00:30:22.070 --> 00:30:24.114
the an Anzio landing winds
up being two divisions only.

578
00:30:24.114 --> 00:30:26.992
the an Anzio landing winds
up being two divisions only.

579
00:30:26.992 --> 00:30:28.702
a drop in the bucket.

580
00:30:34.875 --> 00:30:38.253
- The Allied force at
Anzio lands on an empty beach.

581
00:30:38.253 --> 00:30:41.048
There are almost no
Germans in front of it.

582
00:30:41.048 --> 00:30:42.841
Surprise has been achieved.

583
00:30:45.469 --> 00:30:46.887
- Speed is
of the essence.

584
00:30:46.887 --> 00:30:49.806
As soon as you land. you
must get off the beachhead

585
00:30:49.806 --> 00:30:52.601
as quickly as possible.
strike inland.

586
00:30:53.810 --> 00:30:56.480
One jeep patrol
actually gets as far

587
00:30:56.480 --> 00:30:57.773
as the outskirts of Rome.

588
00:30:57.773 --> 00:31:01.651
So clearly. there is a
route of advance open.

589
00:31:03.153 --> 00:31:04.488
- The
commander of the invasion

590
00:31:04.488 --> 00:31:07.324
is General John Lucas.

591
00:31:07.324 --> 00:31:10.202
- Instead of driving
boldly into the interior

592
00:31:10.202 --> 00:31:13.080
and seizing the high ground
over the Anzio beachhead.

593
00:31:13.080 --> 00:31:15.832
General Lucas stays put.

594
00:31:15.832 --> 00:31:18.251
- His thought is. "I
need to secure this port.

595
00:31:18.251 --> 00:31:20.504
'cause that is how we
will be reinforced".

596
00:31:20.504 --> 00:31:21.922
and so he sits.

597
00:31:23.006 --> 00:31:25.717
As he sits. the German
commander Kesselring

598
00:31:25.717 --> 00:31:27.636
will basically pull
all the cooks. bakers.

599
00:31:27.636 --> 00:31:29.387
and candlestick
makers from round Rome

600
00:31:29.387 --> 00:31:32.682
and build them up to pen
in the Anzio landing.

601
00:31:35.435 --> 00:31:38.105
- The Germans have
the high ground again.

602
00:31:38.105 --> 00:31:40.190
and are able to
control the situation

603
00:31:40.190 --> 00:31:43.401
by subjecting the Allied
forces to constant shelling.

604
00:31:46.655 --> 00:31:48.865
- Leading the way in
the German bombardments

605
00:31:48.865 --> 00:31:51.243
were two enormous railroad guns.

606
00:31:51.243 --> 00:31:53.453
known colloquially to the Allies

607
00:31:53.453 --> 00:31:56.331
as Anzio Annie and
the Anzio Express.

608
00:32:04.881 --> 00:32:08.969
These fire a 500-pound
shell 30 miles.

609
00:32:12.973 --> 00:32:16.393
- It would've sounded
like a freight train.

610
00:32:16.393 --> 00:32:19.563
You could hear it kinda
whistling in. and then boom.

611
00:32:23.692 --> 00:32:26.570
- The Allies at Anzio
are sitting in a marsh.

612
00:32:26.570 --> 00:32:28.363
They have no cover.

613
00:32:29.781 --> 00:32:31.950
Around them are mountains
and German artillery.

614
00:32:31.950 --> 00:32:35.203
and the artillery
never stops firing.

615
00:32:36.872 --> 00:32:39.124
- There was nowhere on
the beachhead you could go to

616
00:32:39.124 --> 00:32:41.042
and get respite
from enemy fire.

617
00:32:41.042 --> 00:32:43.003
And so. what you
basically gotta do

618
00:32:43.003 --> 00:32:46.923
is burrow down into the
ground and hold tight.

619
00:32:46.923 --> 00:32:49.843
It was just this
horrendous grind

620
00:32:49.843 --> 00:32:52.846
of being under fire
for 24 hours a day.

621
00:32:56.683 --> 00:32:59.436
- This is as
miserable a position

622
00:32:59.436 --> 00:33:02.105
as any force in World War II
found themselves.

623
00:33:03.648 --> 00:33:05.483
- Anzio is
Churchill's plan.

624
00:33:05.483 --> 00:33:06.985
And he said. famously.
after the event.

625
00:33:06.985 --> 00:33:09.279
"I thought we landed a
wildcat on the shore.

626
00:33:09.279 --> 00:33:11.114
What we got was a beach whale."

627
00:33:16.077 --> 00:33:17.120
- The
Luftwaffe strafes

628
00:33:17.120 --> 00:33:19.080
Allied troops on the beachhead.

629
00:33:21.958 --> 00:33:25.045
Included in the effort to help
Lucas's forces off the beach

630
00:33:27.631 --> 00:33:29.758
is the 99th Fighter Squadron.

631
00:33:30.967 --> 00:33:34.346
part of what will become
known as the Tuskegee Airmen.

632
00:33:35.096 --> 00:33:37.724
- During that era
of segregation.

633
00:33:37.724 --> 00:33:41.811
most African Americans
serve in rear echelon units.

634
00:33:41.811 --> 00:33:44.522
Tuskegee airmen are
frontline fighting units.

635
00:33:44.522 --> 00:33:46.566
and they're changing
everyone's minds.

636
00:33:51.529 --> 00:33:54.407
On one of their mission.
16 of them fly over Anzio.

637
00:33:58.078 --> 00:34:00.205
and then what they find
is the German aircraft

638
00:34:00.205 --> 00:34:01.998
working over the landing craft.

639
00:34:04.000 --> 00:34:07.963
They shoot down 10 of
those German aircraft.

640
00:34:15.762 --> 00:34:17.054
- To the south.

641
00:34:17.304 --> 00:34:19.641
multiple attacks on the
Monte Cassino abbey fail.

642
00:34:23.603 --> 00:34:25.563
The Allies debate
whether to bomb

643
00:34:25.563 --> 00:34:27.440
the mountaintop
Abbey from the air.

644
00:34:29.985 --> 00:34:33.530
- The Benedictine
abbey that sits on Monte Cassino

645
00:34:33.530 --> 00:34:35.282
is a cultural relic.

646
00:34:35.282 --> 00:34:39.159
The law of armed conflict would
say. we don't touch those.

647
00:34:40.911 --> 00:34:43.956
- Of course. this is one
of the most important libraries

648
00:34:43.956 --> 00:34:46.333
of Christian thought
for millennia.

649
00:34:46.333 --> 00:34:48.962
and many civilians had
taken refuge there.

650
00:34:50.714 --> 00:34:52.632
- But the assumption
was that the Germans

651
00:34:52.632 --> 00:34:54.801
were inside the
abbey and using it

652
00:34:54.801 --> 00:34:57.721
as the perfect field
artillery observer's position.

653
00:34:58.722 --> 00:35:00.473
We cannot allow the enemy

654
00:35:00.473 --> 00:35:03.184
to continue to harass
us with artillery fire.

655
00:35:03.184 --> 00:35:05.562
So. the abbey's gotta go.

656
00:35:09.482 --> 00:35:11.693
Allied forces
distributed pamphlets

657
00:35:11.693 --> 00:35:15.071
warning that there
would be a bombardment.

658
00:35:15.071 --> 00:35:16.823
and the residents. they thought.

659
00:35:16.823 --> 00:35:18.533
they're not actually
going to do it.

660
00:35:31.296 --> 00:35:35.050
- Allied bombers flatten
this shrine of Christianity.

661
00:35:38.845 --> 00:35:41.431
The bombing actually
resulted in the killing

662
00:35:41.431 --> 00:35:44.768
of hundreds of civilians who
were taking refuge there.

663
00:35:44.768 --> 00:35:47.812
- Allied
intelligence was wrong.

664
00:35:47.812 --> 00:35:50.065
The German observation posts

665
00:35:50.065 --> 00:35:53.151
had not been inside
the monastery walls.

666
00:35:54.402 --> 00:35:56.363
- The Germans who weren't
occupying the abbey

667
00:35:56.363 --> 00:35:59.324
have now decided to
occupy the rubble.

668
00:35:59.324 --> 00:36:02.202
which is incredibly effective
for defensive purposes.

669
00:36:02.202 --> 00:36:05.080
So the Allies got
the exact opposite

670
00:36:05.080 --> 00:36:06.373
of what they hoped to achieve.

671
00:36:08.750 --> 00:36:10.543
- Bombing the monastery
gets the Allies

672
00:36:10.543 --> 00:36:12.545
no closer to their goal.

673
00:36:12.545 --> 00:36:15.507
At some point. infantry
is going to have to

674
00:36:15.507 --> 00:36:18.843
ascend a mountain
under enemy fire.

675
00:36:27.435 --> 00:36:30.772
- The Allies have
bombed the Monte Cassino abbey.

676
00:36:30.772 --> 00:36:32.482
but the Germans still
hold the summit.

677
00:36:34.734 --> 00:36:36.945
When the weather
improves in May.

678
00:36:36.945 --> 00:36:38.988
the Allies make yet
another assault.

679
00:36:40.323 --> 00:36:42.867
- They take nearly
their entire force in Italy

680
00:36:42.867 --> 00:36:47.205
and cram it into the narrow
western half of the peninsula.

681
00:36:47.205 --> 00:36:50.250
using overwhelming strength now.

682
00:36:50.250 --> 00:36:54.629
tanks. aircraft. ceaseless
waves of artillery bombardment.

683
00:36:56.089 --> 00:36:59.718
- You've got this extraordinary
United Nations of troops.

684
00:36:59.718 --> 00:37:02.387
I mean. people from all
over the world are Cassino.

685
00:37:03.555 --> 00:37:05.598
- We got the
British. we got the Americans.

686
00:37:05.598 --> 00:37:09.602
we got New Zealand Maoris. we
got Canadians. we got Indians.

687
00:37:09.602 --> 00:37:11.604
we got French
Moroccans. Goumiers.

688
00:37:11.604 --> 00:37:13.815
that are wonderful
mountain fighters.

689
00:37:13.815 --> 00:37:17.360
It is one of the places where
Japanese Americans fight.

690
00:37:18.445 --> 00:37:21.448
Who gets assigned Monte
Cassino? The Pols.

691
00:37:24.951 --> 00:37:26.244
- World War II
began in Europe

692
00:37:26.244 --> 00:37:29.205
when Germany invaded Poland.

693
00:37:29.205 --> 00:37:32.000
As much as anyone.
the Polish people

694
00:37:32.000 --> 00:37:34.753
have suffered from the
brutal rule of the Nazis.

695
00:37:36.588 --> 00:37:37.922
- The idea that
Pols

696
00:37:37.922 --> 00:37:39.048
would never miss an
opportunity

697
00:37:39.048 --> 00:37:40.842
to take it back
out on the Germans

698
00:37:40.842 --> 00:37:42.969
for what they did to them
should be lost on no one.

699
00:37:46.931 --> 00:37:48.433
- At Monte Cassino.

700
00:37:48.433 --> 00:37:51.311
the Pols are that
final wave of fighters.

701
00:37:51.311 --> 00:37:53.813
and they. with incredible
bravery and toughness.

702
00:37:53.813 --> 00:37:55.607
go up this
huge inclines.

703
00:38:01.654 --> 00:38:04.282
- As you advance up the
hill. you have to show yourself.

704
00:38:04.282 --> 00:38:06.201
You're gonna be picked
off. you're a sitting duck.

705
00:38:10.747 --> 00:38:12.248
- We're talking
almost 4.000 casualties

706
00:38:12.248 --> 00:38:14.751
for the Polish units attacking
against Monte Cassino.

707
00:38:17.504 --> 00:38:18.797
- The Pols

708
00:38:18.797 --> 00:38:21.007
finally overrun the
ruins of the abbey.

709
00:38:24.135 --> 00:38:26.054
- The Polish flag is
unveiled

710
00:38:26.054 --> 00:38:27.514
on the top of the
monastery.

711
00:38:33.520 --> 00:38:36.105
And they play this very.
very famous bugle call.

712
00:38:36.105 --> 00:38:37.440
HejnaB Mariacki.

713
00:38:37.440 --> 00:38:40.151
which translates to St.
Mary's trumpet call.

714
00:38:40.151 --> 00:38:44.489
It's a symbol of resilience.
of national identity.

715
00:38:44.489 --> 00:38:48.785
of hope for the future.
and of the fight for Poland

716
00:38:48.785 --> 00:38:51.162
for every single Polish person.

717
00:38:55.250 --> 00:38:57.794
And it sounds out
over the monastery

718
00:38:57.794 --> 00:38:59.504
once the fighting has died down.

719
00:39:03.842 --> 00:39:07.428
- The
Gustav Line is broken.

720
00:39:07.428 --> 00:39:08.888
The Americans are finally able

721
00:39:08.888 --> 00:39:11.599
to break out of the
Anzio beachhead.

722
00:39:14.602 --> 00:39:16.104
- There's a plan to
encircle

723
00:39:16.104 --> 00:39:17.564
